Yet another content slider, and a jQuery plugin :-)
But it would make you happy
YepSlider allows you to "slidify" your custom design without polluting it with new html elements or classnames



0- GENERAL USE CASE

Given you have a slider ready html structure like this

<div id="slider">
  <div class="slide-box"></div>
  <div class="slide-box"></div>
  <div class="slide-box"></div>
  <div class="slide-box"></div>

  <a href="#" id="left_arrow"><img src="any_path/any_left_arrow_file.png" /></a>
  <a href="#" id="right_arrow"><img src="any_path/any_right_arrow_file.png" /></a>
</div>

It is up to you to set the CSS styles, along with arrows positionning (After all, that's the main philosophy)



1- SIMPLE SLIDER

  To turn it into a simple slider, you have to inject a wrapper element around the slide boxes

  <div id="slider">
    <div id="slide-boxes-wrapper">
      <div class="slide-box"></div>
      <div class="slide-box"></div>
      <div class="slide-box"></div>
      <div class="slide-box"></div>
    </div>

    <a href="#" id="left_arrow"><img src="any_path/any_left_arrow_file.png" /></a>
    <a href="#" id="right_arrow"><img src="any_path/any_right_arrow_file.png" /></a>
  </div>

  One last thing, take a note from your design the width of the slider visible area, eg we will say 450px

  Now, add this in your application js file

  $("#slider").yepSlider ({
    childrenBoxClass: ".slide-box",
    childrenBoxWidth: 450,
    showMultiple: 1,
    changeBy: 1,
    wrapperElement: "#slide-boxes-wrapper",
    arrowLeftElement: "#left_arrow",
    arrowRightElement: "#right_arrow"
  }) ;

  That'all ! you cal test your page and you'll see.

  Notes:
   - slide boxes MUST be displayed inline, use float:left, or add any class from your CSS library
   - Don't forget setting the slider element and slider boxes height in your CSS (idealy equals)


2 - ADDING SHORTCUTS

  If you wanna add a navigation links to your slider, just add an ul element

  <div id="slider">
    <div id="slide-boxes-wrapper">
      <div class="slide-box"></div>
      <div class="slide-box"></div>
      <div class="slide-box"></div>
      <div class="slide-box"></div>
    </div>
    
    <ul id="slide-nav"></ul>

    <a href="#" id="left_arrow"><img src="any_path/any_left_arrow_file.png" /></a>
    <a href="#" id="right_arrow"><img src="any_path/any_right_arrow_file.png" /></a>
  </div>

  And add to the js those lines

  shortcutsEnabled: true,
  shortcutsUlElement: "#slide-nav",
  shortcutCurrentElementClass: "current"

  Yep will add automatically an unordered list of links
  It's the only time it injects some elements in your design, but don't worry it would be just a very basic structure

  
    
  <ul id="slide-nav">
    <li><a href="#"></a></li>
    <li><a href="#" class="current"></a></li>
    <li><a href="#"></a></li>
    .
    .
    .
  </ul>

  It's also up to you to set the styles and positionning of it in your CSS


3- ENABLING AUTO SLIDING

  So if you want your slide boxes sliding automatically, just add these in your js

  autoSlide: true,
  interSlideDuration: 10 // default is 10
   
  Where interSlideDuration is the time Yep will wait after the last manual click to switch on automatic mode


4- CONCLUSION

That's all, if you have any suggestions or remarks, you're welcome, just email me at kifer.mada@gmail.com

Have fun !
